Having considered the available (Q)SAR models for nanomaterials, it seems that reactivity (of metal oxides) can be predicted using the conduction band energy level (Ec), whereas dissolution can be represented by the formal charge of the cation (or the enthalpy of formation of a gaseous cation of a metal oxide). These two properties can help in classifying and ranking the toxic potency of metal oxide nanoparticles and are also easily accessible.
Overall, it is recommended that (Q)SAR modellers should:
 focus on descriptor development for nanomaterials, these descriptors should reflect the
structure of tested samples, rather than be based on idealized structures;
 include in the (Q)SAR development phase, as many descriptors as possible to account
comprehensively for the structure of nanomaterials;
 contribute to the development and analysis of functional assays and OMICs data;
 focus on modelling nano-bio interactions.
